[[Category:Ada Programming|Standard:Apex]]

{{Japanese kana navigation}}
In this lesson you are going to learn how to read and write さ、し、す、せ、そ. Adding two small lines called {{furi|濁|だく}}{{furi|点|てん}} ''dakuten'', but commonly known simply as {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'', meaning "two marks", causes clear sounds to change to their voiced sound. Thus, adding the {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'' marks to さ、し、す、せ、and そ will produce ざ、じ、ず、ぜ、ぞ.
== Clear sounds == {{Japanese kana | kana= さ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">sa</big> | mnemonic = The horizontal line is a '''sa'''w (sa) cutting through an '''a'''pple tree branch, and the round part is the apple. | example= * さら (sara) plate * さけ (sake) rice wine * さわる (sawaru) to touch | voiced = ざ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">za</big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * ざんねん (zannen) too bad, regrettable * ざんぎょう (zangyou) overtime (work) * ざいがい (zaigai) overseas }} {{Japanese kana | kana= し | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">{{audio|Shi (Japanese).ogg|shi}}</big> | mnemonic = She (shi) has very long hair. | example= * した (shita) below; rude * しぬ (shinu) to die * しる (shiru) to know | voiced = じ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">ji</big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * じぶん (jibun) oneself * じしょ (jisho) dictionary * じごく (jigoku) hell }} {{Japanese kana | kana= す | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">su</big> | mnemonic = * It's someone who committed '''su'''icide by hanging. * Tie a knot to a "T" | example= * する (suru) to do * すみません (sumimasen) excuse me * すごい (sugoi) awesome, terrific * すし sushi | voiced = ず | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">zu</big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * ずるい (zurui) sly, cunning * ずいい (zuii) optional * ずいちょう (zuichou) good omen }} {{Japanese kana | kana = せ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">se</big> | mnemonic = * It's the face of a person named Seth (se). * A guy has his arm wrapped around the girl and says "say you love me" | example= * せんたく (sentaku) laundry * せなか (senaka) back (of the body) * せまい (semai) confined, small, cramped | voiced = ぜ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">ze</big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * ぜひとも (zehitomo) by all means * ぜんぶ (zenbu) all, entire * ぜん (zen) Zen (Buddhism) }} {{Japanese kana | kana= そ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">so</big> | mnemonic = * There are '''SO''' many lines at the top of this symbol, and '''SO''' few at the bottom. * Think to the sign of "'''Zo'''rro" plus a fox tail * The zig-zag of a '''sew'''ing stitch. |- valign="top" ! bgcolor="#CCCCFF" | Example: | example= * そら (sora) sky * そば (soba) Japanese buckwheat noodles * そと (soto) outside | voiced = ぞ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">zo</big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * ぞう (zou) elephant * ぞうき (zouki) internal organs * ぞうり (zouri) sandals }}
[[Category:Japanese|Hiragana 03]]

{{Japanese kana navigation}}
In this lesson you are going to learn how to read and write た、ち、つ、て、と. Adding two small lines called {{furi|濁|だく}}{{furi|点|てん}} ''dakuten'', but commonly known simply as {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'', meaning "two marks", causes clear sounds to change to their voiced sound. Thus, adding the {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'' marks to た、ち、つ、て、and と will produce だ、ぢ、づ、で、ど.
== Clear sounds == {{Japanese kana | kana = た | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''ta'''</big> | mnemonic = * It's a stylized version of the lowercase letters ''t'' and ''a''. The artist drew a curved ''t'' and neglected to close the ''a'' on either side. | example = * たこ (tako) octopus * たぬき (tanuki) raccoon dog * たね (tane) seed | voiced = だ | voiced_sound = <big><big>da</big></big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * だいがく (daigaku) university, college * だいこん (daikon) Japanese radish * だく (daku) to hug }} :'''Note:''' In Japan, the ''t'' is crossed first, not last. {{Japanese kana | kana = ち | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">{{audio|Chi (Japanese).ogg|'''chi'''}}</big> | mnemonic = * It's a backwards ''c'' with a cross on top. The horizontal line is drawn first, and the backwards ''c'' is drawn in the same stroke as the vertical line of the cross. * ''chi'' translates as ''blood'', and this is a man raising his blood pressure by yelling. * Your little sister's birthday is today, so you write a ''5'' on the card because ''she'' is 5 years old. * It's like a '''chi'''ld's attempt at writing a ''5''. | example = * ち (chi) blood * ちいさい (chiisai) small, little * ちず (chizu) map | voiced = ぢ | voiced_sound = <big><big>ji</big></big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * ち<u>ぢ</u>む (chijimu) to shrink * ち<u>ぢ</u>れげ (chijirege) curly hair * はな<u>ぢ</u> (hanaji) nosebleed }} {{Japanese kana | kana = つ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">{{audio|Tsu (Japanese).ogg|'''tsu'''}}</big> | mnemonic = * Tsunami- this shows the crashing wave of a tsunami. * Your ' ''tsu'' 'oup bowl fell and all the soup spilled, so now it's on it's side and empty. *its a man sneezing Aaah'tsu! | example = * つえ (tsue) walking stick, magic wand * つき (tsuki) moon * つくえ (tsukue) desk | voiced = づ | voiced_sound = <big><big>zu</big></big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * かな<u>づ</u>ち (kanazuchi) hammer * かん<u>づ</u>め (kanzume) canned food * つ<u>づ</u>り (tsuzuri) spelling ''In modern Japanese language, no words start with "づ" and only few have it.'' }} {{Japanese kana | kana = て | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''te'''</big> | mnemonic = * Looks like the capital letter ''T''. * It's a broken '''te'''nnis racket. | example = * てちょう (techou) notebook * てつ (tetsu) iron, steel * てぶくろ (tebukuro) gloves | voiced = で | voiced_sound = <big><big>de</big></big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * でんわ (denwa) telephone * でる (deru) to go out, to leave * でんぱ (denpa) radio wave }} {{Japanese kana | kana = と | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''to'''</big> | mnemonic = * It's a toe (to) with a splinter stuck in it. * It resembles a toenail. When thinking of "to", think toenail. | example = * とけい (tokei) clock, watch * とこや (tokoya) barber * とびら (tobira) door | voiced = ど | voiced_sound = <big><big>do</big></big> | voiced_mnemonic = | voiced_example = * どうぐ (dougu) tool, instrument * どうぶつ (doubutsu) animal * どく (doku) poison }}
== Double Consonants == By adding a small "っ" (''tsu'') in front of a syllable, it causes the subsequent consonant to double. This is called the sokuon ({{furi|促音|そくおん}}). This kana results in a slight pause between the two consonants (a double consonant pause). There is an exception for the kana ''ち''. Instead of having a 'cch', a ''~tch'' is used.
A couple examples are かった (''katta'') and しっけ (''shikke'').
[[Category:Japanese|Hiragana 04]]

{{Japanese kana navigation}}
In this lesson you are going to learn how to read and write は、ひ、ふ、へ、ほ. Adding two small lines called {{furi|濁|だく}}{{furi|点|てん}} ''dakuten'', but commonly known simply as {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'', meaning "two marks", causes clear sounds to change to their voiced sound. Thus, adding the {{furi|点々|てんてん}} ''tenten'' marks to は、ひ、ふ、へ、and ほ will produce ば、び、ぶ、べ、ぼ. Adding a small circle called a {{furi|半|はん}}{{furi|濁|だく}}{{furi|点|てん}} ''handakuten'', but commonly known simply as a {{furi|丸|まる}} ''maru'', "circle" causes clear sounds to change to their plosive sound. Thus, adding a {{furi|丸|まる}} ''maru'' to は、ひ、ふ、へ、and ほ will produce ぱ、ぴ、ぷ、ぺ、ぽ.
{{Japanese kana | kana = は | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''ha'''</big> | mnemonic = * It looks like Ha, but the left arm of the H is broken, and the a is squeezed under the right arm. * It's a stand-up comic, with a microphone on a stand to his left. Ha ha! * It's a missionary, holding up a cross and laughing, "Ha!" * A person is wearing a '''ha'''t. | example =: * はこ (hako) box * はね (hane) wing * はる (haru) springtime | voiced = ば | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''ba'''</big> | voiced_example =: * ばか (baka) fool * ばしゃ (basha) carriage * ばら (bara) rose | plosive = ぱ | plosive_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''pa'''</big> | plosive_example =: * ぱちんこ (pachinko) slotmachine type game * かっぱ (kappa) water imp (in Japanese folk tales) * らっぱ (rappa) trumpet }} :'''Note:''' "は" is pronounced ''wa'' when used as a particle. {{Japanese kana | kana = ひ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">{{audio|Hi (Japanese).ogg|'''hi'''}}</big> | mnemonic = * Somebody's mouth as they say "hi!" really loudly. Just remember that the 'i' is pronounced like 'ee'. * Someone smiling wide at a good joke, 'Heeheehee'. He thought it funny to be (bi) hit by (bi) a piece (pi) of pie. | example = * ひと (hito) person * ひめ (hime) princess * ひる (hiru) daytime | voiced = び | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%">'''bi'''</big> | voiced_example = * びじゅつ (bijutsu) fine arts * びしょう (bishou) beautiful * びん (bin) bottle | plosive = ぴ | plosive_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''pi'''</big> | plosive_example = * えん<u>ぴ</u>つ (enpitsu) pencil * しんぴ (shinpi) mystery * ねんぴ (nenpi) mileage }} {{Japanese kana | kana = ふ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">{{audio|Fu (Japanese).ogg|'''fu'''}}</big> | mnemonic = * The squiggly line looks like a snake - think of the game Snake. The other lines are the food (fu) that the snake is going after. * The squiggly line leads to the top of Mt. '''Fu'''ji. * It looks like an upside question mark, asking who? ('''fu'''?) | example =: * ふうふ (fuufu) married couple * ふえ (fue) flute, whistle * ふく (fuku) clothes, uniform | voiced = ぶ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''bu'''</big> | voiced_example = * ぶき (buki) weapon * ぶた (buta) pig * ぶん (bun) sentence | plosive = ぷ | plosive_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''pu'''</big> | plosive_example = * しん<u>ぷ</u> (shinpu) priest * あっ<u>ぷ</u>く (appuku) subdue * せん<u>ぷ</u>うき (senpuuki) electric fan }} {{Japanese kana | kana = へ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''he'''</big> | colspan="3" | | mnemonic = * '''He'''he, that guy's mustache looks funny - it's longer on one side than the other. * It is an arrow pointing to '''he'''aven. | example =: * へい (hei) fence * へそ (heso) navel * へや (heya) room | voiced = べ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''be'''</big> | voiced_example =: * べんきょう (benkyou) study * べんじょ (benjo) toilet * べんとう (bentou) traditional box lunch | plosive = ぺ | plosive_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''pe'''</big> | plosive_example = * ぺきんご (pekingo) Mandarin Chinese * ぺらぺら(の) (perapera) fluent; talkative * ぺてんし (petenshi) swindler }} {{Japanese kana | kana = ほ | sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''ho'''</big> | mnemonic = * It's a '''hobo''' standing next to a lamp '''po'''st. * The stand-up comic (は) is even funnier when he puts on a silly hat. Ho ho! * Think mini-golf. The line on the left is the putter, the lines on the right are the flag, and the circle is the hole (ho). * It's so '''ho'''t the person is wearing two hats (は). | example = * ほうき (houki) broom * ほね (hone) bone * ほん (hon) book | voiced = ぼ | voiced_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;"> '''bo'''</big> | voiced_example =: * ぼう (bou) stick * ぼく (boku) A first personal pronoun usually used by men * ぼろ (boro) defect | plosive = ぽ | plosive_sound = <big style="font-size: 150%;">'''po'''</big> | plosive_example =: * しっ<u>ぽ</u> (shippo) tail * ぶん<u>ぽ</u>う (bunpou) grammar * こどもっ<u>ぽ</u>い (kodomoppoi) childish }}
